 ENDF/B-VI MOD 2 Evaluation, July 1999, M.B. Chadwick,P.G.Young   8325 1451
                                                                  8325 1451
  This evaluation provides a complete representation of the       8325 1451
nuclear data needed for transport, damage, heating, radioactivity 8325 1451
and shielding applications over the incident neutron energy range 8325 1451
from 1e-11 to 150 MeV. The evaluation from 20 to 150 MeV is built 8325 1451
on the previous evaluation below 20 MeV by Smith, Smith, and      8325 1451
Guenther. Above 20 MeV, production cross sections and             8325 1451
emission spectra are given for neutrons, protons, deuterons,      8325 1451
tritons, alpha particles, gamma rays, and all residual nuclides   8325 1451
produced (A>5) in the reaction chains. To summarize, the ENDF     8325 1451
sections with non-zero data above 20 MeV are:                     8325 1451
                                                                  8325 1451
  MF=3 MT=  1  Total Cross Section                                8325 1451
       MT=  2  Elastic Scattering Cross Section                   8325 1451
       MT=  3  Nonelastic Cross Section                           8325 1451
       MT=  5  Sum of Binary (n,n') and (n,x) Reactions           8325 1451
                                                                  8325 1451
  MF=4 MT=  2  Elastic Angular Distributions                      8325 1451
                                                                  8325 1451
  MF=6 MT=  5  Production Cross Sections and Energy-Angle         8325 1451
               Distributions for Emission Neutrons, Protons,      8325 1451
               Deuterons, and Alphas; and Angle-Integrated        8325 1451
               Spectra for Gamma Rays and Residual Nuclei That    8325 1451
               Are Stable Against Particle Emission               8325 1451
                                                                  8325 1451
  The evaluation is based on nuclear model calculations that have 8325 1451
been benchmarked to experimental data, especially for n+209Bi and 8325 1451
p +209Bi reactions [Ch99b]. We use the GNASH code system [Yo92],  8325 1451
which utilizes Hauser-Feshbach statistical, preequilibrium and    8325 1451
direct-reaction theories. Spherical optical model calculations ar 8325 1451
used to obtain particle transmission coefficients for the Hauser- 8325 1451
Feshbach calculations, as well as for the elastic proton angular  8325 1451
distributions.                                                    8325 1451
  Cross sections and spectra for producing individual residual    8325 1451
nuclei are included for reactions. The energy-angle-correlations  8325 1451
for all outgoing particles are based on Kalbach systematics       8325 1451
(Ka88).                                                           8325 1451
  A model was developed to calculate the energy distributions of  8325 1451
all recoil nuclei in the GNASH calculations [Ch96]. The recoil    8325 1451
energy distributions are represented in the laboratory system in  8325 1451
MT=5, MF=6, and are given as isotropic in the lab system. All     8325 1451
other data in MT=5,MF=6 are given in the center-of-mass system.   8325 1451
This method of representation utilizes the LCT=3 option approved  8325 1451
at the November, 1996, CSEWG meeting.                             8325 1451
  Preequilibrium corrections were performed in the course of the  8325 1451
GNASH calculations using the exciton model of Kalbach [Ka77,      8325 1451
Ka85], validated by comparison with calculations using Feshbach,  8325 1451
Kerman, Koonin (FKK) theory [Ch93].  Discrete level data from     8325 1451
nuclear data sheets were matched to continuum level densities     8325 1451
using the formulation of Ignatyuk et al. [Ig75] and pairing and   8325 1451
shell parameters from the Cook [Co67] analysis. Neutron and       8325 1451
charged-particle transmission coefficients were obtained from the 8325 1451
optical potentials, as discussed below.  Gamma-ray transmission   8325 1451
coefficients were calculated using the Kopecky-Uhl model [Ko90].  8325 1451
                                                                  8325 1451
SOME Bi209-SPECIFIC INFORMATION CONCERNING THE EVAL.              8325 1451
                                                                  8325 1451
An optical potential developed by Chiba [Ch99] for neutron        8325 1451
reactions on lead was modified for use on bismuth. For            8325 1451
protons, the Becchetti-Greenlees potential was used, and          8325 1451
above 20 MeV  the relativistic medium-energy global               8325 1451
proton potential of Madland [Ma88] was used. A detailed           8325 1451
study of direct reactions on bismuth was undertaken.              8325 1451
Collective excitations of excited vibrational states were         8325 1451
treated using the weak-coupling model, with a h9/2 proton         8325 1451
coupled to a 208Pb core. This allows extensive deformation-       8325 1451
length information on direct reactions on  208Pb to be used       8325 1451
in the bismuth calculations. The direct and preequilibrium        8325 1451
reaction mechanisms were tested through comparisons with          8325 1451
neutron emission data at 26 MeV, measured by Marcinkowski [Ma96]. 8325 1451
We used the Ignatyuk [Ig75] level density formalism.              8325 1451
                                                                  8325 1451
Kim et al.[Ki98] measured 209Bi(n,xn) excitation functions up     8325 1451
to 150 MeV. Comparisons with calculations provide a               8325 1451
stringent test of the reaction theories embodied within GNASH.    8325 1451
Our results agree with the measurements well. The incident        8325 1451
proton channel calculations were tested through comparisons       8325 1451
with (p,xn) and (p,xp) emission spectra at 90 MeV [Wu77,Ka83].    8325 1451
Again, agreement was good.                                        8325 1451
